def ref_heat_curve(ref_filename,eliminate_point=252):
    x = np.loadtxt(ref_filename, skiprows=1)
    heat_time =x[:,0]
    heat_temp =x[:,1]
    heat_vel = x[:,3]
    
    ind=np.where(heat_time<140)[0]
    ind = np.delete(ind,252)
    heat_temp = heat_temp[ind]
    heat_vel = heat_vel[ind]
    
    return heat_time, heat_temp, heat_vel

### 2. Load simple stepped cooling data

def simple_lume(lume_filename):
    x = np.loadtxt(lume_filename, skiprows=1)
    time =x[:,0]
    temp =x[:,1]
    vel = x[:,3]
    return time, temp, vel

### 3. Plot velocity graph

def velocity_graph(filename, ref_filename, para=0, temp_up=850, temp_low=750):
    time, temp, vel = simple_lume(filename)
    heat_time, heat_temp, heat_vel = ref_heat_curve(ref_filename)
    vel_fcc, fit_coef = fc2.fit_velocity(temp,vel,temp_up,temp_low)
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    ax.plot(heat_temp, heat_vel,'o',markersize=1,color='red',label = 'ref_heat')
    ax.plot(temp, vel+para,'o',markersize=1,color='blue',label = 'Measured')
    ax.plot(temp,vel_fcc+para,color='green',label='FCC' )
    ax.axis(ymin =5,ymax=6,xmin=150,xmax=950)
    plt.xlabel('Temperature[$^\circ$C]')
    plt.ylabel("Ultrasound velocity[m/s]")
    
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

def ind_lumefra_graph(filename, ref_filename, para=0, temp_up=850, temp_low=750):
    time, temp, vel = simple_lume(filename)
    heat_time, heat_temp, heat_vel = ref_heat_curve(ref_filename)
    vel_fcc, fit_coef = fc2.fit_velocity(temp,vel,temp_up,temp_low)
    
    df1 = pd.DataFrame({'Time':time, 'Temp':temp,'vel_c':vel+para,'vel_fcc':vel_fcc+para}).sort_values(by='Temp')
    df2 = pd.DataFrame({'Temp':heat_temp,'vel_bcc':heat_vel}).sort_values(by='Temp')
    df3 = pd.merge_asof(df1,df2,on='Temp')
    df3['fr'] = (df3['vel_c']-df3['vel_fcc'])/((df3['vel_bcc'])-df3['vel_fcc'])
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    ax.plot(df3['Time'],df3['fr'],'o',markersize=1,color='black',label='fr_LUMet' )
    ax.axis(ymin =0,ymax=1)
    plt.xlabel('Time[s]')
    plt.ylabel("Fraction Transformed[-]")
    
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

### 6.5 fraction calculation from velocity

def lumefra_calc(filename, ref_filename, para=0, temp_up=850, temp_low=750):
    time, temp, vel = simple_lume(filename)
    heat_time, heat_temp, heat_vel = ref_heat_curve(ref_filename)
    vel_fcc, fit_coef = fc2.fit_velocity(temp,vel,temp_up,temp_low)
    
    df1 = pd.DataFrame({'Time':time, 'Temp':temp,'vel_c':vel+para,'vel_fcc':vel_fcc+para}).sort_values(by='Temp')
    df2 = pd.DataFrame({'Temp':heat_temp,'vel_bcc':heat_vel}).sort_values(by='Temp')
    df3 = pd.merge_asof(df1,df2,on='Temp')
    df3['fr'] = (df3['vel_c']-df3['vel_fcc'])/((df3['vel_bcc'])-df3['vel_fcc'])
    
    return df3

def exit_fr(filename, ref_filename,para=0, 
            temp_up = 800, temp_low=720, 
            hold_st=174, hold_time=600,
            ext_st = 580, ext_end=599):
    ''' The function extract the value of the fraction transformed at the exit of isothermal holding.    
    '''
    df = lumefra_calc(filename,ref_filename, para=para, temp_up=temp_up, temp_low=temp_low)
    df['Time'] =df['Time'] - hold_st
    df = df[df['Time']<hold_time]
    df = df[(df['Time']>ext_st)&(df['Time']<ext_end)]
    exit_fr = df['fr'].mean()
    return exit_fr

JMAK analysis for 2.0%Mn steels¶

The JMAK analysis is performed on the velocity development during transformation progress for isothermal holding conditions. The velocity change is defined by $$ \Delta V_{i} = v_{i} - v_{st} $$ , where \$v_{i} \$ is the instantaneous velocity and \$v_{st} \$ is the initial velocity when the isothermal holding starts. \$v_{st}\$ is always the minimum velocity during the isothermal holding. For the sake of the subsequent calculation, the following function crop the part during the isothermal holding out of the whole data. In order to normalize the velocity change, the maximum velicity change \$ \Delta V_{max} \$ is calculated by averaging the velocities from the last 10 seconds during the isothermal holding. The normalized velocity change is defined by

$$ \Delta V_{norm,i} = \frac{\Delta V_{i}}{\Delta V_{max}} $$

In the laser ultrasonic technique, this normalized velocity change can be considered as the normalized fraction transformed.

In [7]:
# dV development method
def norm_dv(filename, ref_filename, para = 0,inc_time=0,  
                 temp_up = 800, temp_low=720,
                 hold_st=174, hold_time=600,
                 ext_st = 580, ext_end=599):
    lume = lumefra_calc(filename, ref_filename, para= para, temp_up= temp_up, temp_low=temp_low)
    lume['Time'] = lume['Time'] - (hold_st + inc_time)
    lume = lume[lume['Time']>0]
    lume = lume.sort_values(by='Time')
    lume['dv'] = lume['vel_c']-lume['vel_c'].min()
    lume = lume[lume['Time']<ext_end]
    exit_dv = lume['dv'].max()
    exit_dv = lume[(lume['Time']>ext_st)&(lume['Time']<ext_end)]['dv'].mean()
    lume['dv_norm'] = lume['dv']/exit_dv
    
    return lume

lume_1 = norm_dv(ST_650c_600s_20Mn, ref_filename,hold_st=174, ext_end=599)

All three conditions achieves 1% transformed at the second data point. Therefore, in the present study, the incubation time, in which the fraction transformed is less than 1% transformed, is eliminated from the JMAK equation in the subsequent analysis. The following function creates the columns of lnt and product defineed by \ $ ln(t) : $ Naturallogarithm for the time \ $ product{i} := ln( ln(\frac{1}{1-\Delta V_{norm, i}})) $

def JMAK_pre_dv(lume):
    lume['lnt'] = np.log(lume['Time'])
    lume['product'] = np.log(np.log(1/(1-lume['dv_norm'])))
    return lume
lume_1_JMAK = JMAK_pre_dv(lume_1)
lume_2_JMAK = JMAK_pre_dv(lume_2)
lume_3_JMAK = JMAK_pre_dv(lume_3)

def time_for_fr_10_90(lume):
    index_10 = lume[lume['dv_norm']>0.10].index[0]
    index_90 = lume[lume['dv_norm']>0.90].index[0]
    lnt_10 = lume.loc[index_10,'lnt']
    lnt_90 = lume.loc[index_90,'lnt']
    return lnt_10, lnt_90

def time_for_fr_10_90_700(lume):
    index_10 = lume[lume['dv_norm']>0.10].index[0]
    index_90 = lume[lume['dv_norm']>0.90].index[0]
    lnt_10 = lume.loc[index_10,'lnt']
    lnt_90 = lume.loc[index_90,'lnt']
    return lnt_10, lnt_90

To take acount for the temperature dependency of the intercept of the JMAK plot (the natural logarithm of the rate parameter), the liniear fitting can be applied. The obtained relations can be expressed as follows. $$ ln(b) = -0.0206(\frac{1}{K})T(K) + 17.109 $$ By using the above relationship, the JMAK model is applied to the normalized fraction for each condition. $$ X_{i,norm} = 1 - exp(-b_{i}t^n)$$ where i corresponds to each temperature condition. More specifically, $$ X_{650,norm} = 1 - exp(-0.149t^{0.88})$$ $$ X_{675,norm} = 1 - exp(-0.089t^{0.88})$$ $$ X_{700,norm} = 1 - exp(-0.053t^{0.88})$$

The following code compares the JMAK fitting for the normalized fraction transformed with the measurement.

def sparse_lume(lume, n1=3, n2=20,threshold=0.7):
    lume1 = lume[lume['dv_norm']<threshold]
    lume2 = lume[lume['dv_norm']>=threshold]
    lume1 = lume1[::n1]
    lume2 = lume2[::n2]
    lume3 = pd.concat([lume1, lume2])
    return lume3

def norm_dv_25Mn650(filename, ref_filename, para =-0.035,inc_time=0,  
                    temp_up = 800, temp_low=700,
                    hold_st=174, hold_time=600,
                    ent_st = 0, ent_end =1,
                    ext_st = 560, ext_end=599):
    lume = lumefra_calc(filename, ref_filename, para= para, temp_up= temp_up, temp_low=temp_low)
    lume['Time'] = lume['Time'] - (hold_st + inc_time)
    lume = lume[lume['Time']>0]
    lume = lume.sort_values(by='Time')
    ent_dv = lume[(lume['Time']>ent_st)&(lume['Time']<ent_end)]['vel_c'].mean()
    lume['dv'] = lume['vel_c']-ent_dv
    lume = lume[lume['Time']<ext_end]
#    exit_dv = lume['dv'].max()
    exit_dv = lume[(lume['Time']>ext_st)&(lume['Time']<ext_end)]['dv'].mean()
    lume['dv_norm'] = lume['dv']/exit_dv
    
    return lume

def sparse_lume(lume, n1=3, n2=20,threshold=0.7):
    lume1 = lume[lume['dv_norm']<threshold]
    lume2 = lume[lume['dv_norm']>=threshold]
    lume1 = lume1[::n1]
    lume2 = lume2[::n2]
    lume3 = pd.concat([lume1, lume2])
    return lume3

lume_1s = sparse_lume(lume_1,n1=4, threshold=0.6)

def time_for_fr_10_90(lume):
    index_10 = lume[lume['dv_norm']>0.10].index[0]
    index_90 = lume[lume['dv_norm']>0.90].index[0]
    lnt_10 = lume.loc[index_10,'lnt']
    lnt_90 = lume.loc[index_90,'lnt']
    return lnt_10, lnt_90

def norm_dv_25Mn650(filename, ref_filename, para =-0.035,inc_time=0,  
                    temp_up = 800, temp_low=700,
                    hold_st=174, hold_time=600,
                    ent_st = 0, ent_end =1,
                    ext_st = 560, ext_end=599):
    lume = lumefra_calc(filename, ref_filename, para= para, temp_up= temp_up, temp_low=temp_low)
    lume['Time'] = lume['Time'] - (hold_st + inc_time)
    lume = lume[lume['Time']>0]
    lume = lume.sort_values(by='Time')
    ent_dv = lume[(lume['Time']>ent_st)&(lume['Time']<ent_end)]['vel_c'].mean()
    lume['dv'] = lume['vel_c']-ent_dv
    lume = lume[lume['Time']<ext_end]
#    exit_dv = lume['dv'].max()
    exit_dv = lume[(lume['Time']>ext_st)&(lume['Time']<ext_end)]['dv'].mean()
    lume['dv_norm'] = lume['dv']/exit_dv
    
    return lume

def norm_dv_25Mn650(filename, ref_filename, para =-0.035,inc_time=0,  
                    temp_up = 800, temp_low=700,
                    hold_st=174, hold_time=600,
                    ent_st = 0, ent_end =1,
                    ext_st = 560, ext_end=599):
    lume = lumefra_calc(filename, ref_filename, para= para, temp_up= temp_up, temp_low=temp_low)
    lume['Time'] = lume['Time'] - (hold_st + inc_time)
    lume = lume[lume['Time']>0]
    lume = lume.sort_values(by='Time')
    ent_dv = lume[(lume['Time']>ent_st)&(lume['Time']<ent_end)]['vel_c'].mean()
    lume['dv'] = lume['vel_c']-ent_dv
    lume = lume[lume['Time']<ext_end]
#    exit_dv = lume['dv'].max()
    exit_dv = lume[(lume['Time']>ext_st)&(lume['Time']<ext_end)]['dv'].mean()
    lume['dv_norm'] = lume['dv']/exit_dv
    
    return lume
